 p You can invoke further operations as desired, such as querying the individual cluster member's status.    

 p Also, in addition to querying, you can also  a href="http:/ ublib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/wasinfo/v7r0/topic/com.ibm.websphere.javadoc.doc/web/apidocs/com/ibm/websphere/management/AdminClient.html#addNotificationListener(javax.management.ObjectName,%20javax.management.NotificationListener,%20javax.management.NotificationFilter,%20java.lang.Object)" rel="nofollow" register notifications /a  so that your program can be notified when certain events happen, such as a change in state of clusters, servers, or applications.

 p They are present in the servletcontainer itself. Even more, the servletcontainer is at its own actually the whole concrete implementation of the Servlet API.    

 p In case of  a href="http://tomcat.apache.org" rel="nofollow" Tomcat /a  (which is  a href="http://tomcat.apache.org/download-70.cgi" rel="nofollow" open source /a ), the implementation of  code request.getSession() /code  is provided by the  a href="http://tomcat.apache.org/tomcat-7.0-doc/api/org/apache/catalina/connector/Request.html" rel="nofollow"  code org.apache.catalina.connector.Request /code  /a  class. In the current Tomcat 7.0.25 release it look like this:    

